{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":12709,"duration_api_ms":12273,"num_turns":3,"result":"The bug is clear from both the source and the sanitizer report.\n\n**ROOT CAUSE:** `program.cpp:12` — The `destroy_list` function walks the linked list by reading `cur->next` **after** deleting `cur` on line 13. The loop's increment expression `cur = cur->next` is evaluated after `delete cur` has already freed that memory, so the read of `cur->next` is a use-after-free. The node is deallocated first, then its `next` pointer is dereferenced to advance the loop.\n\n**LOCAL FIX:** Save `cur->next` into a temporary variable before deleting `cur`:\n```cpp\nstatic void destroy_list(Node *head) {\n    for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; ) {\n        Node *next = cur->next;  // save next before freeing\n        delete cur;\n        cur = next;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**GLOBAL FIX:** Use `std::unique_ptr<Node>` (or `std::forward_list<int>` from the standard library) to manage node ownership. With `unique_ptr`, each node owns its successor via `std::unique_ptr<Node> next`, and destroying the head recursively (or iteratively via `std::unique_ptr::reset`) releases the chain in safe ownership order — the pointer to the next node is read before ownership is released, making use-after-free structurally impossible. More broadly, replacing raw owning pointers with RAII smart pointers throughout the codebase eliminates the entire class of \"free then dereference\" bugs at compile time.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"187abe1b-8815-4e65-bd90-ed1b8fcba718","total_cost_usd":0.0588366,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10462,"cache_read_input_tokens":31967,"output_tokens":667,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10462,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":371,